         <div xml:id="main">
            <head type="incipit">
               <supplied reason="XTF-compatibility">South Yarra, ¶  17th September, 1892. ¶  ¶ The plant just received from you, dear Mr Martin, is a South African  ¶ Homeria,  ¶ which is very near  ¶ H. lineata ¶  in affinity. ¶  I have heard that in ...</supplied>
            </head>
            <p rend="number" xml:lang="en">92.09.17</p>
            <p rend="correspondent" xml:lang="en">To David Martin</p>
            <space dim="vertical" unit="lines" quantity="1"/>
            <space dim="vertical" unit="lines" quantity="1"/>
            <p rend="letter"
               style="font-family: Geneva; font-size: 12pt; text-align: end; "
               xml:lang="en">
               <note xml:id="ftn1" type="footnote" n="1">
                  <p rend="Footnote"
                     style="font-family: Geneva; margin-left: 0.3346in; margin-right: 0in; text-indent: -0.3346in; font-size: 9pt; "
                     xml:lang="en">Letter not found. The text given here was printed as Appendix A in McAlpine (1893), p. 11 (B93.03.03).</p>
               </note>South Yarra,<note xml:id="ftn2" type="footnote" n="2">
                  <p rend="Footnote"
                     style="font-family: Geneva; margin-left: 0.3346in; margin-right: 0in; text-indent: -0.3346in; font-size: 9pt; "
                     xml:lang="en">Melbourne.</p>
               </note> 17th September, 1892.</p>
            <space dim="vertical" unit="lines" quantity="1"/>
            <p rend="letter"
               style="font-family: Geneva; font-size: 12pt; "
               xml:lang="en">
               <space dim="horizontal" extent="tab"/>The plant just received from you, dear Mr Martin, is a South African <seg style="font-style: italic; ">Homeria, </seg>which is very near <seg style="font-style: italic; ">H. lineata</seg> in affinity.<note xml:id="ftn3" type="footnote" n="3">
                  <p rend="Footnote"
                     style="font-family: Geneva; margin-left: 0.3346in; margin-right: 0in; text-indent: -0.3346in; font-size: 9pt; "
                     xml:lang="en">Peter MacOwan in Capetown told <space unit="chars" quantity="1"/>Martin, 22 December 1892, 'Your plant is <seg style="font-style: italic; ">
                        <space unit="chars" quantity="1"/>Homeria collina, Vent., </seg>var.<seg style="font-style: italic; "> miniata</seg>.' (McAlpine (1893), p. 11). <seg style="">M apparently sought information from MacOwan who sent him transcriptions of Pappe (1857), pp. 37 and 59, that were reproduced as Appendix C in McAlpine (1893), pp 11-13. </seg>M's botanical description at Appendix E, pp.14-15 <space unit="chars" quantity="1"/>is of <seg style="font-style: italic; ">Homeria collina, Vent., </seg>var.<seg style="font-style: italic; "> miniata </seg>(B93.03.04).</p>
                  <p rend="Footnote"
                     style="font-family: Geneva; margin-left: 0.3346in; margin-right: 0in; text-indent: -0.3346in; font-size: 9pt; "
                     xml:lang="en">
                     <space dim="horizontal" extent="tab"/>
                     <space dim="horizontal" extent="tab"/>
                     <space dim="horizontal" extent="tab"/>See also M to D. Martin, 1 November 1892. </p>
               </note> I have heard that in their native country occasionally pasture animals have suffered from these kinds of plants; but no poison cases have hitherto come under my own notice. I would strongly advise that they be destroyed at the place where they must have strayed from — some adjoining garden.</p>
            <p rend="valediction"
               style="font-family: Geneva; font-size: 12pt; margin-left: 1.75in; margin-right: 0in; text-indent: 0in; "
               xml:lang="en">(signed) FERD. VON MUELLER.</p>
            <space dim="vertical" unit="lines" quantity="1"/>
            <space dim="vertical" unit="lines" quantity="1"/>
            <space dim="vertical" unit="lines" quantity="1"/>
            <p rend="plant%20names" xml:lang="en">
               <name key="Homeria%20lineata">Homeria lineata</name>
            </p>
         </div>
      </body>
